  - energy(...), delta_energy(...), and convergence_window(...) expose diagnostics: how much energy the
    oscillator has, whether energy changed, and whether recent changes look settled.
  - _state_vectors(...), _diagonal_vector(...), _forcing_vector(...), and _normalize_mode(...) are
    internal contract enforcers. They normalize inputs, reject bad shapes, resolve forcing, and keep
    mode names consistent.

  Design Decisions That Stand Out

  The strongest design decision is the A / G boundary. A means stiffness/frequency; G means damping/
  forgetting. That is exactly aligned with the updated AGENTS.md instruction to preserve this boundary
  and explain what this package does specifically relative to LinOSS.

  The second major decision is no stateful model class. Everything is explicit: arrays in, arrays and
  metrics out. That makes the code easier to test, replay, port, and embed in host systems.

  The third is dependency discipline. The core solver is NumPy-only and does not import host
  frameworks, agent runtimes, graph databases, event buses, JAX, or Discretax. That matches docs/
  architecture.md:1.

  The fourth is observability through metrics. Each step returns energy before/after, signed energy
  delta, mode, and damping mode. That gives developers and cognition-oriented readers a concrete way to
  inspect whether the state is ringing, dissipating, or settling.

  Relation to LinOSS: this is not “the LinOSS implementation” and should not be described as inventing
  LinOSS or D-LinOSS. It is a NumPy runtime implementation of LinOSS-style oscillator stepping with
  explicit damping support.

